sentences: Lewis died of lung failure in August 1971.
He first recorded in 1917 with Earl Fuller's Jazz Band, who were attempting to copy the sound of the city's newest sensation, the Original Dixieland Jass Band.
By 1919, Lewis was leading his own band, and had a recording contract with Columbia Records, which marketed him as their answer to the Original Dixieland Jass Band who recorded for Victor records.

Lewis's clarinet playing barely evolved beyond his style of 1919 which in later years would sound increasingly corny, but Lewis certainly knew what good clarinet playing sounded like, for he hired musicians like Benny Goodman, Jimmy Dorsey, Frank Teschemacher, and Don Murray to play clarinet in his band.

Ted Lewis' band was second only to the Paul Whiteman band in popularity during the 1920s, and arguably played more real jazz with less pretension than Whiteman, especially in his recordings of the late 1920s.
Lewis recorded for Columbia from 1919–1933.
He was on Decca 1934 into the 1940s.

In 1932, Lewis recorded "In a Shanty in Old Shanty Town", which he had performed in the film "The Crooner" with his orchestra.
Around 1928, Lewis noticed an usher named Eddie Chester mimicking his movements during his act.
Ted Lewis and His Orchestra were one of the featured entertainers at the 1939 Golden Gate International Exposition – Pageant of the Pacific on Treasure Island.
Lewis kept his band together through the 1950s, and continued to make appearances in Las Vegas and on television (appearing as the mystery guest on What's My Line?
in 1956, for example) into the 1960s.

Musical numbers cut from the feature were released by Universal separately on September 3, 1941, in a short subject entitled  Is Everybody Happy?

In 1943 Columbia Pictures mounted a feature-length biographical film of Lewis—yet again titled Is Everybody Happy?—with actor Michael Duane portraying the bandleader and lip synching to Lewis's recordings.
There is an extended caricature of Lewis in the Warner Brothers short Speaking of the Weather (Tashlin, 1937), playing Plenty of Money and You.
Lewis married Adah Becker (1897 – May 31, 1981) in 1915.
Lewis died in his sleep in New York on August 25, 1971, of lung failure at the age of 81.
His wife Adah, who died on May 31, 1981, rests beside him.
The Ted Lewis Museum, located across the street from where he was born, was dedicated on June 5, 1977.

sentences: Theodore Leopold Friedman (June 6, 1890 – August 25, 1971), known as Ted Lewis, was an American entertainer, bandleader, singer, and musician.
At the start of the 1920s, he was considered by many people without previous knowledge of jazz (that is to say, most of America) to be one of the leading lights of hot jazz.

Lewis's clarinet playing barely evolved beyond his style of 1919 which in later years would sound increasingly corny, but Lewis certainly knew what good clarinet playing sounded like, for he hired musicians like Benny Goodman, Jimmy Dorsey, Frank Teschemacher, and Don Murray to play clarinet in his band.
For years, his band also included jazz greats Muggsy Spanier on trumpet and George Brunies on trombone.

Ted Lewis' band was second only to the Paul Whiteman band in popularity during the 1920s, and arguably played more real jazz with less pretension than Whiteman, especially in his recordings of the late 1920s.
